Prerequisites
Docker Desktop installed and running
That's it — Python and Node are not needed locally (Docker handles everything)
Step 1 — Fix the .env file
The current backend/.env has placeholder passwords. Open it and replace the three REPLACE*WITH*\* values:

backend/.env

SECRET_KEY=9b9a9915a46ae8afdafe0c2e4f31b8181b35cdd42949da10b73c29e66c052083

QR_SECRET=any-random-string-here-change-this

ENVIRONMENT=development

DATABASE_URL=postgresql+psycopg://app_user:myapppass123@db:5432/appdb

POSTGRES_USER=postgres
POSTGRES_PASSWORD=mypostgrespass123
POSTGRES_DB=appdb

APP_DB_PASSWORD=myapppass123
The two passwords must match: APP_DB_PASSWORD in the URL and the standalone field must be identical. Use any password you like for local dev.

Step 2 — Start all services
From the project root (where docker-compose.yml lives):

docker compose up --build
This:

Builds the FastAPI backend image (installs all Python deps)
Pulls the PostgreSQL 17 image
Starts the Node 20 container that runs the Vite dev server
Runs the DB init SQL (db/init/01_roles.sql) which creates the app_user role
First run takes ~2 minutes to download images and install packages.

Step 3 — Run database migrations (first time only)
Open a second terminal while the containers are running:

docker compose exec backend alembic upgrade head
You should see alembic printing each migration revision. This creates all tables, enums, constraints, and RLS policies.

Step 4 — Access the app
What URL
Frontend (customer + staff UI) http://localhost:3000
Backend API http://localhost:8000
API docs (Swagger) http://localhost:8000/docs
Health check http://localhost:8000/health

Step 5 — Create your first restaurant + admin user
Use the Swagger UI at http://localhost:8000/docs or curl. You need a SUPERADMIN user first.

Create SUPERADMIN directly in the DB (one-time setup):

docker compose exec db psql -U postgres -d appdb

INSERT INTO restaurants (id, name, slug, is_active)
VALUES (gen_random_uuid(), 'Platform', 'platform', true);

-- Get the restaurant id just inserted
-- Then insert the superadmin (replace the UUID and hash accordingly)
Easier: use the /superadmin/restaurants endpoint after seeding a superadmin manually. Here's the full seed command:

docker compose exec backend python -c "
from app.db.session import SessionLocal
from app.models.user import User
from app.models.restaurant import Restaurant
from app.models.settings import RestaurantSettings
from app.core import security
from app.models.enums import Role
import uuid

db = SessionLocal()
r = Restaurant(name='Platform', slug='platform', is_active=True)
db.add(r); db.flush()
s = RestaurantSettings(restaurant_id=r.id)
db.add(s)
u = User(restaurant_id=r.id, email='super@admin.com',
password_hash=security.hash_password('admin1234'),
role=Role.SUPERADMIN)
db.add(u); db.commit()
print('SUPERADMIN created:', u.email)
db.close()
"
Then log in at http://localhost:3000 with super@admin.com / admin1234, and use the Superadmin panel to create restaurants.

Day-to-day commands

# Start everything

docker compose up

# Start in background

docker compose up -d

# Stop

docker compose down

# View backend logs

docker compose logs -f backend

# Run migrations after a schema change

docker compose exec backend alembic upgrade head

# Open a DB shell

docker compose exec db psql -U postgres -d appdb

# Rebuild backend image (after adding a dependency)

docker compose up --build backend
